{"review_threads":[{"is_resolved":true,"is_outdated":true,"is_collapsed":true,"comments":[{"body":"These assertions are checking the stub `main` module injected by `tests/conftest.py`, not the real `main.py` in the repo, so they don’t actually validate bot setup behavior. If the goal is to cover the real entrypoint, import `main` directly (with patches for `data.load`/env to avoid side effects) and assert against `main.BotWithAbstractors` from the real module.","path":"tests/test_main.py","author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796038"},{"body":"Implemented.","path":"tests/test_main.py","author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806602"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":true,"is_outdated":true,"is_collapsed":true,"comments":[{"body":"This fixture deletes and re-imports `data` to escape the global autouse patches in `tests/conftest.py`, but it relies on autouse fixture execution order to work (if the conftest patch runs after this reload, `data.save/load/update_game_status` will still be mocked and these tests become ineffective). Make the ordering/intent explicit (e.g., add an opt-out marker that `conftest._patch_data` respects, or explicitly depend on the patch fixture) so these tests can’t become flaky or silently stop testing the real `data` module.","path":"tests/test_data.py","author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796043"},{"body":"Implemented.","path":"tests/test_data.py","author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806615"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":true,"is_outdated":true,"is_collapsed":true,"comments":[{"body":"`discord.User.id` is an `int` in production; setting it to a string here can hide type-mismatch bugs in the permission check logic and makes the test less representative. Use an integer ID consistently, and consider adding an explicit regression test that the owner (non-admin) can stop their own game, since that’s a distinct code path from the admin case.\n```suggestion\n    async def test_owner_can_stop_own_game(self, mock_bot, mock_interaction):\n        owner = MagicMock(spec=discord.User)\n        owner.id = 222\n        abstractor = MagicMock()\n        abstractor.channel = 123\n        abstractor.running = True\n        abstractor.owner = owner\n        abstractor.game = MagicMock()\n        abstractor.game.running = True\n        mock_bot.abstractors = [abstractor]\n\n        cog = GamesCog(mock_bot)\n        mock_interaction.channel = MagicMock()\n        mock_interaction.channel.id = 123\n        mock_interaction.user = owner\n\n        await cog.stop.callback(cog, mock_interaction)\n        assert abstractor.game.running is False\n\n    @patch.dict(\"os.environ\", {\"ADMIN_USERS\": \"111\"})\n    async def test_admin_can_stop_game(self, mock_bot, mock_interaction):\n        owner = MagicMock(spec=discord.User)\n        owner.id = 222\n```","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796046"},{"body":"Implemented.","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806618"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":true,"is_outdated":true,"is_collapsed":true,"comments":[{"body":"The coverage omit path looks incorrect: there is no `classes/test_turnmanager.py` in this repo (the test lives under `tests/classes/test_turnmanager.py`), and `tests/` isn’t part of `source` anyway. This line is likely ineffective/misleading—either remove it or correct it to the intended file/path.\n```suggestion\n\n```","path":"pyproject.toml","author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796048"},{"body":"Implemented.","path":"pyproject.toml","author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806620"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"The new acted-player guard is good, but the class docstring above `InvestigateRole.on_selected()` still claims this override is “never actually called” due to the SelectRole lambda binding. Since `handle_button_click()` calls `self.on_selected(...)`, this override *is* invoked and now also accepts `action_view`; please update/remove that outdated note to avoid misleading future changes.","path":"classes/roles/__init__.py","line":313,"author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796049"},{"body":"Not implemented.","path":"classes/roles/__init__.py","line":313,"author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806621"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":true,"is_outdated":true,"is_collapsed":true,"comments":[{"body":"This globally injects a fake `main` module into `sys.modules`, which means `import main` (and anything that imports `BotWithAbstractors` from `main`, like the cogs) will not exercise the real `main.py` implementation. That makes the suite’s “main setup” coverage misleading and can mask integration issues between real `BotWithAbstractors` and the cogs. Consider avoiding a global `sys.modules` override (e.g., import the real `main` with targeted patching of `data.load`/env, or monkeypatch `sys.modules['main']` only in tests that need it).","path":"tests/conftest.py","author":"copilot-pull-request-reviewer","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:47:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969796053"},{"body":"Implemented.","path":"tests/conftest.py","author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T16:57:30Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2969806625"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"In what circumstances should `on_selected` be called with `action_view = None`? Right now, this would allow the sheriff to multi-act.\n\nIt looks like other on_selected implementations have this problem too, so this might be fine as-is? But I think it's worth asking the question in case there is something you are specifically handling here and that entire codepath needs a rethink.","path":"classes/roles/__init__.py","line":314,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:07:55Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T19:07:55Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970005543"},{"body":"oops, still learning Github's UI -- looks like I need to use \"start a review\" on my first comment to create a batch rather than immediately sending them out one at a time. sorry for the noise, will batch up the remainder.","path":"classes/roles/__init__.py","line":314,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:09:10Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T19:09:10Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970008146"},{"body":"Oh my god. This makes sense. I will fix this when I get back home.","path":"classes/roles/__init__.py","line":314,"author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T21:36:41Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T21:36:41Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970311574"}],"total_count":3},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Remove this. The \"no alive players\" state isn't a meaningful state for the Doctor to be acting in, so it's an awful default. Every test that actually wants to use `get_alive_players` is explicitly listing some other set, and that seems like a reasonable approach to me -- it keeps the test-specific test setup in the tests that use it.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":10,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:15:26Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970018563"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Import this at the top of the file.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":86,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:29:17Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970042433"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I'm a little surprised that this doesn't have to set up `mock_player`'s user ID. That means that nothing checks that the player who is purportedly taking in action is the _correct_ player for the incoming interaction. `SpecialActionButton.callback` fences that off, but, like, maybe I'm just paranoid but I think it would be better to catch if something goes horribly wrong with game coordination and folks start acting for each other? Should there be a check in `on_selected` for that?","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":108,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:39:44Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970063705"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"`assert JESTER.win_condition(mock_player, [])` would create a more immediately obvious error message if the test fails. ","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_jester.py","line":19,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T19:41:43Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970067667"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Why mock `Player()`? It's very nearly just a `dataclass`! Using real objects as much as possible gives a better chance of identifying real bugs. Reserve mocks for things that are too hard to actually test.\n\nCreate a new file, `testutils.py`, containing:\n\n```\ndef new_test_player(name: str | None = None, id: int | None = None):\n    user = MagicMock()\n    if id is not None:\n        user.id = id\n    user.name = name or \"UNTITLED.TXT\"\n    return Player(user)\n```\n\nWith suitable imports to make that actually work. I suspect that you will have an easier time writing this by hand than having an AI do it.\n\nThen import `.testutils` in your role tests and use `new_test_player` everywhere you need a test player. There is no reason to use `@pytest.fixture` to inject a `mock_player` parameter to your tests, just create `mock_player = new_test_player()` and you're back where you started, `mock_player = new_test_player(\"very_good_username\", 90210)` if you want a higher-fidelity mock player.\n\nThen replace _all_ the spots where you're using MagicMock to create a half-assed fake player -- like, well, about three lines later, see my next comment...","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":20,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:01:37Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970115619"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"...so, here, after doing the `new_test_player` thing, this should instead be\n```\np1 = testutils.new_test_player()\np2 = testutils.new_test_player()\np3 = testutils.new_test_player()\n```\n\nalthough you are free to insert names and IDs if you want. I think you will have an easier time writing this _once_ by hand, then pointing it to the same pattern where it shows up in the _next_ function and telling it that you have a better way to set up Player objects for tests and you want it to change everything that sets up \"raw\" mocks for Players -- for example, `test_doctor_get_options_with_last_saved` -- and make it use `testutils.new_test_player()` instead, like you updated `test_doctor_get_options_no_last_saved` to do. AI models do _very well_ when you give them an example and ask them to generalize (Gemini Flash is specifically optimized for this, I note), so \"get it right once and then have the AI do the rest\" is my preferred approach; it's easier IMO than just trying to argue with the AI until it figures out what would actually be a good design.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":29,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:03:04Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970118341"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"And this pattern keeps showing up, here and in multiple test files. Please update it to not mock out the easily-created Player objects everywhere the code currently does this. I promise you will be much happier with the tests as a result, because they will catch a wider variety of ways for you to shoot yourself in the foot by making incompatible changes. Mocks, much like AI models, are perfectly happy to keep telling you what you want to hear, using more real objects in your tests will discover issues with the actual implementation, rather than the hypothetical fantasy implementation that exists only for tests. They're a great tool for getting rid of dependencies on external services, like Discord or OpenAI, or for taking out very large complicated monoliths (like TurnManager) that you have to isolate from a test, but Player is definitely not one of those monoliths.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":47,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:05:38Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970123924"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Mocking out `discord.Interaction` is definitely worth it, _that's_ not a type we want to deal with and the async handling of `response.edit_message` also really needs to be part of the mock, but hopefully we'll have a lot of tests that want to mock interactions. Please create `new_mock_interaction()` in `testutil` and use it where suitable.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_doctor.py","line":105,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:07:12Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970126243"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"And here, `assert not JESTER.win_condition(mock_player, [])` would work better, for the same reason.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_jester.py","line":25,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:09:40Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970132183"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"etc., you get it by now.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_jester.py","line":31,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:09:50Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970132457"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These weren't tested for the Doctor. Should they be removed here or should the Doctor get equivalent tests?","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_jester.py","line":51,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:10:46Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970134478"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"\"can_act\" doesn't really have anything to do with action buttons, and we already have `test_jester_is_special`, so this test should be removed.\n\nSpecifically, I don't think `can_act` is useful to test on the Jester at all. I've filed an Issue about the bad semantics of `can_act`; testing _what_ it does on a role that never has a night action doesn't make any sense since it should never be called, and the current implementation is guaranteed to give the strange result \"yes, it can act\" on something that, by definition, has no way to act. So writing a test that specifically verifies these strange, undesirable semantics, on a type for which `can_act` _should_ never be called, entrenches that problem deeper. In general, it's better to avoid tests that require a stupid behavior that is specifically not reachable in production -- \"overconstraining\" behavior can put up barriers to fixing former design issues. It's easy enough to delete the test, but the test communicates that there is some good reason this behaves this way; I am personally confident that is false, but an AI model trying to \"improve\" the code is less likely to be so sure, so it's better not to entrench the behavior. I would assume that an AI generated this test specifically because it thought the behavior might be important rather than undesirable, so it made sure to verify it _because_ it's surprising!\n\nI'm rambling, sorry. I just wanted to point this out, because I think it's an important thing in AI development: the AI is very bad at figuring out the difference between \"things that are load-bearing because they are important in a subtle way\" and \"things that are load-bearing because the rest of the code has detailed workarounds for how stupid this design is\" so it tends to entrench bad design deeper, and tests reinforcing a bad idea tend to create some confirmation bias. So one of the most important things you can do when evaluating AI-generated code is to ask whether something is a good idea or if it is doing something entirely related to an accident of history that is better off excised rather than reinforced.\n\nAaaaanyway, after removing this check then all that's left is the `is_special` check which is already tested up on line 38, so the entire test dies as a result.\n\nThe \"has no special action button\" thing might be worth testing, but this isn't the way to do it -- you'd need a test that _actually runs through the \"decide whether to draw a special action button\" routine_ and this isn't doing that, that code is somewhere over in `views.py` and I think it's not even a function of its own, making it hard to test. (Nothing wrong with pulling it out into a separate function so it *can* be tested -- that's usually a very good idea tbh -- but this patch is huge already so I would strongly recommend doing it separately.)","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_jester.py","line":56,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:18:06Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970151851"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"\"MafiaGame\" is complicated enough that mocking it out makes sense (at least to some extent), but consider moving the \"create a mock\" logic to my hypothetical `testutils.py` since I see other tests created here also use it. AI should be pretty good at doing this.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_mafia.py","line":11,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:36:39Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970194354"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Should there be any assertion about `target`'s alive-ness? If I understand correctly, `handle_selection` alone _shouldn't_ change it because the target doesn't know they're dead yet. Which you can and should add an assertion about, along with a comment about why `target` has apparently, by design, survived their death.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_mafia.py","line":56,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:42:48Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970207441"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"As with The Jester, remove this test.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_mafia.py","line":45,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:43:15Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T20:45:36Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970208265"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I note that `make_player` should also be replaced with calls to `testutils.new_test_player`! The AI generating this test recognized the need for a non-fixtural \"generate player for test\" implementation, but didn't generalize this realization. Did you ask the AI to go through and consider whether it would benefit from refactoring the code it just created, including tests? Maybe it just isn't designed to recognize \"common test nouns\" as something that should be combined and isn't designed to recognize \"over-mocking is bad\", I dunno. Although I kinda want to know which model this is so I can avoid it. 😁","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":15,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T20:52:29Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T21:06:41Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970225778"},{"body":"The model was Opus 4.6, but I think the actual problem was its thinking mode. I set it to max thinking effort, but a lot of benchmarks show that the high thinking effort produces more refined results. I'll keep this in mind when I use opus later on.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":15,"author":"wbrous","created_at":"2026-03-21T21:41:40Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T21:41:40Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970321622"},{"body":"Oof, I thought Opus would do better than that, but I suppose I haven't tried to use it to do mass test writing, and usually I give much narrower sets of instructions to AI models so I'm not stuck, say, reviewing three thousand lines of code at once. Well, we'll get through it. Telling _Sonnet_ exactly what to trace and to prefer to mock only at API boundaries -- Discord, OpenAI, HTTP -- if at all practical is probably the way to go for cleaning up the really, really overmocked things.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":15,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:21:42Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:21:42Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970681875"}],"total_count":3},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"See previous note on merging `mock_game` (in `test_mafia.py`) with this `make_game` into a new `testutils.new_mock_game()` function. Looking at this, I recommend setting up its signature as follows:\n\n```\ndef new_mock_game(*, players: list[Player] | None = None)  -\u003e Player:\n    if players is None:\n        players = []\n    # ...and now the rest of the mock, merging the setup from the other things\n```\n\nThe `*` parameter is a marker for \"all the parameters after this point can only be used by name, not by position\" -see [the spec](https://peps.python.org/pep-3102/) if you want way more detail than you ever cared about. (I read things like that for fun because I am a very, very strange person but you might want to do more productive things with your life, up to you)\n\nThis means that calls actually using the `players` parameter would have to be explicit about it:\n\n```\nmock_game = testutils.new_mock_game(players = map(testutils.new_test_player, [\"Kukla\", \"Fran\", \"Ollie\"]))\n```\n\nBut this means you can add as many named \"this test needs to override this specific thing\" parameters as you want without having to keep those parameters \"in order\" as you add more, shuffle them around, change what the mock is actually mocking vs. using real implementations for, etc.; my thought is that this parameter list is _likely_ to grow out of control in the future, so it will only be feasible to use with keyword syntax, so just plan for that _now_ and then nobody has to go back and fix callers if they want to reorganize the parameter list and it communicates that the API might secretly be [a gigantic mess](https://docs.python.org/3/library/subprocess.html#using-the-subprocess-module) and named parameters are necessary to tame it. Here, I think I see A Gigantic Mess in our future, so let's just plan for it.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":22,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T21:06:04Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T21:06:42Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970252592"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Wait up, that's weird, why is this one specific alignment special?\n\nThis test is accurately covering a behavior in `roles/__init__.py` I just think the behavior is weird. I appreciate the test pointing it out. \n\nI searched the code and it looks like nothing is using the `roles.NEUTRAL` declaration and literally everything uses `Alignment.NEUTRAL` instead? If true, that's great! Delete it, and delete this test to go with it. Although maybe that should be a patch of its own, this one is huge already and it's possible I overlooked something so it would be risky enough to be worth isolating. I mean, you've already watched me make that mistake with `extract_choice`...","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":36,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T21:12:43Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970264017"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This behavior is actually pretty bad, isn't it?\n\nSince Roles are intended to be singletons, I think their `__hash__` and `__eq__` should be deleted -- they should be compared only by object identity. Defining them as an equivalency class based on name seems like a bad time.\n\nI went and spent a while verifying this as best I could, since weird uses of operator overloading and hashing can be hard to find. I couldn't find any, and Gemini 3.1 Pro thinks I'm right, for whatever that's worth. So maybe delete those methods and all of the tests for `__hash__` and `__eq__` behaviors since the object identity behaviors are probably better?\n\nThen again, this patch is already huge, so maybe just delete the tests and delete the methods separately, just to keep stuff a little more manageable.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":73,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T21:20:53Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970278399"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Per my other notes on can_act, this test seems like a bad idea.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":117,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:09:28Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970382495"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This would also be a spot to use `testutil.new_test_player()` once it exists.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":121,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:10:06Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970383984"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These don't seem to test much of anything. With everything mocked out, it's hard to figure out what they _should_ test. I infer it's a \"make sure it doesn't crash\" thing, but maybe it _should_ crash if it gets weird fake objects instead of objects that mean something? I think these tests should be removed, unless they can be made more meaningful.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":137,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:10:49Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970385794"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"...again, I'm kind of peeved that the model creating this test didn't stop to think about whether \"make a player object for a test\" should be centralized into a test support library, and that it also didn't stop to think about whether it should be mocked out at all. (this is another testutils.new_test_player() thing, but I'm pointing it out because asking the AI to refactor all the obvious \"player as MagicMock()\" patterns might miss this one, since it doesn't have the same shape.)","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":159,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:14:09Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970391393"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Wait, what does the type checker think is wrong here? I'm suspicious this directive hides a real problem.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":1,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:15:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970394408"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"ಠ_ಠ","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":190,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:16:40Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970396306"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"So, this is an attempt to intercept the calls to SelectView, but it only captures the most recent one. It doesn't check whether SelectView has been constructed some number of times other than \"once\". If it's constructed twice and only the second one has the correct parameters, the bad construction will be called. Also, this doesn't test whether SelectView itself is constructed successfully.\n\nI spent a while tracing and as far as I can tell, SelectView is \"inert\" -- its constructor alone doesn't require the Discord.py library to have a real live connection or something. So that means we should intercept it, rather than completely replace it:\n\n```\nreal_select_view = views_module.SelectView\nbuilt = []\n\nclass FakeSelectView(real_select_view):\n    def __init__(self, options, callback):\n        super().__init__(options, callback)\n        built.append({\n            options: options,\n            callback: callback,\n            item: self,\n        })\n\nmonkeypatch.setattr(views_module, \"SelectView\", FakeSelectView)\n```\n\nLater on in the test, check `len(built)` and subsequently use built[0] where `built` is being used in the current implementation.\n\nThis approach preserves as much \"real code\" as possible, detecting if the SelectView constructor or the way it is being used here causes something illegal in the construction sequence. It's possible I mis-traced something, so if this actually fails because part of the Discord API isn't hooked up right, see if you can monkeypatch out just that part; if you can't, you can go back to the \"fake object does not inherit from the real one\" approach, but I think it is worth trying not doing that and finding out what happens.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":197,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:37:20Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970433836"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Oh, yeah, if you unify \"create a mock interaction\" somewhere, this would be one of the places to change. AI should have no problems finding it.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":227,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:38:20Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970435717"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Should action_view also get a unified \"mock it out for me\"? Or, on second thought, does it genuinely need to be mocked? (Possibly yes, maybe handle_selection does work that has to be intercepted.)","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":230,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:39:15Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970437498"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This state is contradictory.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":279,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:43:10Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970444368"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This shouldn't be a separate test. Instead of setting up what we think the implementation detail of \"enough of a fake action view to keep track of player counts\" looks like, then setting it up with a \"this player already acted\" state, it would be more effective to append the end of this test from `r.handle_selection = AsyncMock()` on downwards to the end of the test currently named `test_on_selected_handles_selection_and_marks_player_acted`. Then you're verifying that the logic prevents doing it twice in a much more direct way: by trying to do it twice! None of this messing around with emulating the environment, just _do_ it.\n\nMocks are a necessary evil, not a first resort. They make tests harder to maintain and less realistic. Look for opportunities to use real behaviors whenever feasible.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":269,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:46:28Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970450038"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Don't mock out `extract_choice`! It's a pure function that is doing something straightforward and completely compatible with the test. It's also an implementation detail-- we don't _care_ if this used `extract_choice`, we care that it did the right thing, and extract_choice is one of the ways it can do that. This test should leave `extract_choice` alone, while continuing to verify that `handle_selection` indeed observed that `\"Alice\"` was selected.\n\nBut it's not like there are a lot of _other_ choices that can be made. Add another player to the scenario prepared for this test so it is conceivably possible to represent a wrong answer.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":305,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:50:03Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970455650"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This test should also verify `player.role_state[\"pending_save\"]` to make sure that was correctly updated in the \"do it twice\" case too.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":348,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:52:00Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970458492"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Is this behavior actually desirable, or should it behave more like the SaveRole, above? Mafia votes are a special case anyway, the only night-action kill that uses the codepath is the one-shot Vigilante.\n\nIt might be better to leave this as-is but file a bug to fix it, since adding thousands of lines of tests might not be the best patch to bury more behavior changes in, but the test is certainly an opportunity for me to ask about it.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":395,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:53:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970460725"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Why mock? Use a real role singleton instead.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":426,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:55:15Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970463461"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"As above.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":451,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:55:53Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970464486"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This entire batch of tests is undesirable and overspecified. Individual roles can, in their own tests, verify their own values; this just creates a second place to test them. It also creates an obstacle to adding more roles. There isn't some rule that we want to enforce that \"there are exactly six possible roles\", or that \"they are listed in exactly this order\" (although we do care about the order a little bit in some of the iteration logic, but we should deal with that by testing that logic instead). All this test does is verify we haven't changed the literal code -- which is worse than useless. It will push AI models into doing stupid, stupid things to try to \"keep\" these tests passing, and whether they fix the tests or do something _incredibly_ dumb when trying to \"implement a new role\" is a coin toss at best.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":503,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T22:59:00Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:00:13Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970472262"},{"body":"I'd copy this.  Likely nothing truly relies on the jester being called \"Jester\" -- it could be named \"Pagliacci\" and the code would still be correct.\r\n\r\nI'd add that I've practically seen Claude behave in worrying ways to try to keep this category of test passing at my actual job. My best guess as to why: Claude is _very_ reluctant to change the behavior of code that has at least one callsite, and these changes are a very visible example of a callsite.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_roles_init.py","line":503,"author":"nyeogmi","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:49:16Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:49:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970701908"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Illogical, per my equivalent comment in test_roles_init","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_sheriff.py","line":89,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:03:15Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970483706"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Per my comment in test_roles_init, maybe just actually try to call `on_selected` twice (possibly with a new mock for interaction.response.edit_message on the second one)? Actually, I think this applies to similar tests in `test_doctor.py` and I just didn't think of it at that time.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_sheriff.py","line":79,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:04:24Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970484904"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"See my previous comments on `can_act`.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_townsperson.py","line":37,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:05:02Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970485853"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Inline the assertion, per my previous recommendations. (I'll stop repeating this one, but please apply it wherever the pattern recurs)","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_vigilante.py","line":25,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:06:02Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970487367"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This kind of points out how weird it is to filter out the \"already shot\" case in `handle_button_click` rather than `handle_selection`. Probably nothing to do for it right now but I wanted to flag it.","path":"tests/classes/roles/test_vigilante.py","line":73,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:07:34Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970490662"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This will only work as long as there is no actual game data file, since `data.load` is not patched out. This test should patch `data.load` to return `{}` instead., I think.","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":43,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:10:00Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970494965"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"AI might miss rewriting some of these to use the standard test object creator functions, if you write them and then use AI to rewrite, so I wanted to point it out, since these look a little different from the other spots these objects are mocked out inline.","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":51,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:11:17Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970497141"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Probably better not to pin this behavior down with a test. (Unlike the behavior on `True` which, although an equally strange design decision, is _very_ load bearing and the test is necessary even though the codepath should almost certainly be changed. I'm against overtesting things that are undesirable _and_ unnecessary to treat as constraints, but things that are only undesirable but are also load-bearing are usually _more_ important to test since they are more likely to be broken by someone later assuming nothing could _really_ be depending on that screwy API behavior, right? and of course it's critical.\n\nThis is another reason _not_ to overtest implementation details and unreachable, undesired code -- if you regularly include tests for things that should not actually be tested, you train future maintainers to ignore test failures and just change the tests whenever they fail, and that's just \"not having tests\" with extra steps.","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":64,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:13:27Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970501035"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I suspect that `turnmanager` might want a central \"mock out Thing of this type\" helper too.","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":74,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:18:42Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970508811"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"The other test uses `monkeypatch` instead. Probably better to pick one and stick with it (I recommend `monkeypatch` for consistency with `pytest` in general).\n\nAlso, please investigate whether StartGameView _actually needs to be mocked out._ Maybe there's a narrower scope of mocking possible?","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":69,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:19:51Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970510576"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These are all just \"test it doesn't actually crash\" right now. Is there some more specific behavior that can be observed for HTTP errors?","path":"tests/classes/test_abstractor.py","line":141,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:31:08Z","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:17Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970527330"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Well, lookie there! The thing we actually wanted was right here all along.\n\nI think randomizing `user.id` is bad, since it makes this impossible to use in a test that actually cares about user ID. It doesn't even guarantee IDs are unique. Consider:\n\n```\n# in testutil.py\nid_counter: int = 100  # reset automatically from conftest.py\n\ndef make_player(*, name: str = \"\", role: Role = TOWN, alive: bool = TRUE, is_ai: bool = FALSE, id: int | None = NONE) -\u003e Player:\n    if is_ai:\n        user = AIAbstraction(\"gpt-4o-mini\", name)\n    else:\n        user = MagicMock(spec=discord.Member)\n        user.name = name\n        if id is None:\n            id = id_counter\n            id_counter += 1\n        user.id = id\n    # and then the rest of make_player\n    # ....\n\n# in conftest.py\n@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\ndef reset_id_counter():\n    testutil.id_counter = 100\n```\n\nNow when IDs are unspecified for a non-AI test player, they will start at 100 per test case and count up from there, deterministically.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":23,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:50:32Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970558946"},{"body":"I would agree -- usually the most helpful kind of fake is a fake that implements a simplified but realistic version of the behavior. For instance, a good \"mafia player\" fake might have this behavior:\r\n\r\n- Has a favorite player, defaulting to \"any player named Alice.\"\r\n- Always uses any valid action, if available, on their favorite player.\r\n- Has an ID assigned sequentially out of some pool which is fresh for every test. (you can do this by having your Pytest fixtures produce a factory function, instead of just a single instance)\r\n\r\nThis has the advantage that it's (1) deterministic (2) strong enough to test cases like \"a player who preferentially uses role abilities on themself\" (3) low on the amount of initialization required. (it's just a single \"favorite player.\")","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":23,"author":"nyeogmi","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:52:56Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:52:57Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970704261"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{